#Text=Rescue workers search wreckage of Brazilian air crash
#Text=Tuesday , October 3 , 2006
#Text=Gol Transportes Aéreos Flight 1907 crashed 1,750km ( 1,100 miles ) north-west of Rio de Janeiro killing all people onboard , on Friday September 29 .
#Text=National Civil Aviation Agency ( ANAC ) has confirmed that the crashed Brazilian airplane did crash into a smaller aircraft .
#Text=Rescue workers and air force personnel are searching the wreckage for bodies
#Text=Search and rescue teams arrive
#Text=Search and rescue teams rappelled down ropes or hacked a way through the rainforest , led by local Indians to reach the wreckage .
#Text=The first people at the scene had to abseil down to clear away trees to allow helicopters to land .
#Text=" It 's extremely difficult to get there , " said Ademir Ribeiro , a foreman on the nearby Jarina ranch , the centre for rescue operations .
#Text=About 80 air force personnel were at the site during the day and about thirty stayed during the night .
#Text=An air force statement says that the first two bodies were recovered on the afternoon of Sunday , October 1 .
#Text=The bodies were taken to an air force base by helicopter .
#Text=Officials say that the investigation would take at least three months .
#Text=Milton Zuanazzi , director of the National Civil Aviation Agency , says that he does not know how long the removal of bodies would take .
#Text=737 Crashed , Legacy made emergency landing
#Text=A Embraer Legacy 600 owned by ExcelAire , a charter company based in Long Island , New York clipped the Boeing 737-800 SFP .
#Text=The Legacy made an emergency landing at Cachimbo air force base with five passengers and two crew on board , none of whom were hurt .
#Text=The Boeing plunged nose first into the rainforest and disintegrated .
#Text=When interviewed by the police , the passengers on the Legacy reported feeling a bump at the time of the collision .
#Text=The pilot landed the plane manually .
#Text=An Air Force statement said that a search of the site showed no signs that the 149 passengers and six crew on board the Boeing 737 could have survived the crash .
#Text=" Neither of the pilots can understand how a 737 could have hit us without them seeing it , " said Joe Sharkey , a journalist for the New York Times , in an email to his wife .
#Text=Mr. Zuanazzi says it 's possible as they were traveling at hundreds of miles an hour .
#Text=" They said they did n't see anything .

column1: #Text=Bill Waldock , aviation safety professor at Embry-Riddle Aeronautical University in Prescott , Arizona , says that the Legacy may have clipped the bigger jet 's horizontal stabiliser — fins that prevent the airplane from pitching up or down .
#Text=" A likely reason why the 737 would depart continuous flight and go vertically into the jungle at that speed would be damage or loss of the horizontal stabiliser , " Mr. Waldock said .
#Text=Relatives flown over crash site
#Text=Relatives of the passengers have complained that they were not being informed about the ongoing search for bodies or the investigation .
#Text=The air force has flown them in groups of six over to the crash site .
#Text=The air force says that it was to show them how difficult it is to reach the crash site .
#Text=" They will be able to see the difficulties of the operation ...
